Project 3: Visual Analysis of Youth Literacy Rates and Annual Percent of GDP Spent on Education

This html page, produced by creating an R markdown document, and using KnitR to knit the file into html. The purpose of this html file, is to show our analysis of two different data sets. One data set is the youth literacy rate by countries for various years. The other data set is the percentage of a countries GDP spent on education for various years. This html also shows the steps required to reproduce our findings, given the same data. Given the variables in both data sets, we were able to query the data base in a few different ways, join the data to gather results, and visualize them using ggplot2.

Data Wrangling set 1:

Below is our first visualization of a subset of the data. The point graph shows a representation of the consumption of LPG between the United States, and the 5 countries sanctioned by the United States over the years 1990-2012. The graph clearly shows the enormous consumption gap between the United States and these countries that have U.S. sanctions.

Data Wrangling set 2:

Below a visualization of a subset of the data. For this visualization, we wanted to observe a global trend for consumption of LPG over the time period 1990-2012. The data clearly shows the same gap, between a few countries that consume vastly more LPG then the remaining majority of countries. This helps visualize the global wealth gap between developed countries, and a majority of underdeveloped or developing countries.

Data Wrangling set 3:

Below is a visualization of a subset of the data. We thought it would be insightful to see how the global financial crisis in 2008 affected some of the worlds largest countries. To our complete surprise, the data visualization showed little to no change in the years following the financial crisis for all countries grouped in the subset used.
